<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900514-0037</DOCNO><DOCID>900514-0037.</DOCID><HL>   Former Norden Executive   Sentenced in `Ill Wind' Case</HL><DATE>05/14/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18</SO><CO>   UTX</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- A former executive of United TechnologiesCorp. was sentenced to six months in prison and fined $5,000for conspiring to obtain inside information about Pentagoncompetition for a Navy contract.   Roger Engel, 49 years old, who was vice president of thecompany's Norden Systems division in Norwalk, Conn., wassentenced by U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton in Alexandria,Va.</LP><TEXT>   The former executive cooperated with the JusticeDepartment's broad investigation of Pentagon procurementfraud, which the department called &quot;Operation Ill Wind.&quot; Hewas the third former Norden executive to plead guilty toparticipating in a conspiracy to obtain inside bidinformation on a roughly $150 million contract to build abattlefield air-traffic control system for the Marine Corps.   The three men said they arranged in 1988 for Norden to paydefense consultant Thomas Muldoon $49,500 to get informationabout the Navy's contract competition from his contacts inthe Defense Department.   Mr. Muldoon was sentenced to 27 months in prison and fined$10,000 in February for participating in an unrelated schemeto bribe a Pentagon procurement official. He is appealing hisconviction.</TEXT></DOC>